### TypeScript — IntersectionObserver + counter animation

In ngAfterViewInit(), set up one IntersectionObserver for all .stat-block elements:

private initStatCounters(): void {
  const blocks = this.el.nativeElement.querySelectorAll('.stat-block');

  const observer = new IntersectionObserver((entries) => {
    entries.forEach(entry => {
      if (entry.isIntersecting) {
        const block = entry.target as HTMLElement;
        
        // 1. Trigger CSS reveal
        block.classList.add('visible');
        
        // 2. Animate the number
        const target = parseInt(block.dataset['target'] ?? '0', 10);
        const countEl = block.querySelector('.stat-count') as HTMLElement;
        this.animateCount(countEl, target);
        
        // 3. Only fire once per element
        observer.unobserve(block);
      }
    });
  }, {
    threshold: 0.3,   // fires when 30% of the block is visible
    rootMargin: '0px 0px -80px 0px'
    // -80px bottom margin: fires slightly before element hits 
    // the very bottom of viewport — feels more responsive
  });

  blocks.forEach((block: Element) => observer.observe(block));
}

private animateCount(el: HTMLElement, target: number): void {
  const duration = 1200;   // ms — total count animation time
  const start = performance.now();
  
  // easeOutExpo — fast start, slow finish (premium feel)
  // do NOT use linear — linear counts feel like a loading bar
  const easeOutExpo = (t: number): number =>
    t === 1 ? 1 : 1 - Math.pow(2, -10 * t);

  const tick = (now: number) => {
    const elapsed = now - start;
    const progress = Math.min(elapsed / duration, 1);
    const eased = easeOutExpo(progress);
    
    el.textContent = Math.round(eased * target).toString();
    
    if (progress < 1) {
      requestAnimationFrame(tick);
    } else {
      el.textContent = target.toString(); // lock to exact value
    }
  };

  requestAnimationFrame(tick);
}

Call initStatCounters() at the end of ngAfterViewInit().
Inject ElementRef as private el: ElementRef in the constructor.

---

### Rules — do not change these

- threshold: 0.3 exactly — lower = fires too early (number counts 
  while offscreen), higher = fires too late (user misses the start)
- easeOutExpo only — this easing makes large numbers feel weighty 
  as they slow down. Linear or easeInOut break the effect.
- observer.unobserve() after firing — each stat counts exactly once.
  If it re-fires on scroll back up, the effect is ruined.
- Label enters 300ms after block becomes visible (transition-delay: 0.3s)
  — this stagger is what makes it feel sequenced, not simultaneous
- The suffix (+ sign) is ALWAYS var(--color-accent) blue — 
  it is the only accent on an otherwise white/grey block

